[1] Cholera, possible - Spain (Andalusia)
Date: Tue 17 Aug 2010
Source: Diario de Cadiz [In Spanish, trans. Corr.SB] [edited]
<http://www.diariodecadiz.es/article/cadiz/769097/la/epidemia/colera/regresa/puerto/real.html>


Unfortunately, cholera has returned to Puerto Real (Cadiz,
Andalusia). Yesterday [16 Aug 2010], the mayor of that town informed
the provincial governor of 2 deaths that due to the disease.

The governor, Fernando de Gabriel, has ordered the isolation of the
population of Puerto Real, and the placing of all merchandise from
that area, under observation. The workers from Puerto Real employed
in La Carraca [a military center for construction and repair of ships
and storage and distribution of ammunition and armament] may not
return to their homes, but will remain in the military establishment
until the cessation of the epidemic. This way they can keep working
and sending their wages to their families.

In La Linea (de la Concepcion) there have been 2 [outbreaks?] of
cholera yesterday [16 Aug 2010] and people have been protesting the
allowed free movement of goods from Gibraltar, the [possible] origin
of the disease. In the rest of the province public health is satisfactory.

--
Communicated by:
HealthMap Alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Most cases of cholera in the developed world are imported.
ProMED-mail awaits for more information regarding microbiologic
confirmation of cholera here. - Mod.LL]

Maps of Spain showing Cadiz can be seen at
<http://blog.willamette.edu/people/klutz/journal/archives/spain_map.jpg> and
<http://healthmap.org/r/02SW>. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]

